Thank you for the update, good to hear we have made progress.
 
For validating the imported project, the main recommendation is to compare the key entities you care about directly between the source and destination after the import. GitLab’s file export/import process is not intended to be used as a full backup mechanism, and not all items are exported in all cases.
 
A practical validation checklist would be:
 
Repository data: compare the default branch, branch count, tag count, and a sample of commit history between source and destination.
Issues and merge requests: compare overall counts and then spot-check a sample for comments, labels, milestones, and attachments.
Wiki and uploads: open a few pages/files directly in the destination project and confirm they render correctly.
Pipelines: compare what you need carefully, because with file export/import only the latest pipeline in merge requests is preserved.
Merge request diffs: only the latest diff version is preserved after file export/import.
 
I understand this may be a GitLab Self-Managed to GitLab Self-Managed migration. Could you please confirm the following so we can validate whether the observed behavior is expected for your migration path?
 
the source GitLab version
the destination GitLab version
whether this was done using project export/import, group export/import, or direct transfer
 
Please also note that the reported GitLab version in the ticket, 14.10.4, is outside the supported range and is no longer supported.
 
